[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426561&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426561&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Forgive me if I misunderstand this issue but:

There is a concern that because there are multiple, disconnected
chaosnets hanging off various Internet sites, that we must thus
qualify a host's chaos host number with a network number.

Somehow this seems misguided since there are of course multiple,
disconnected internets in the world (e.g., many corporations have
their own ethernets running TCP/IP which are not connected to the
DARPA Internet).  When these companies start running domain servers,
we won't need to suddenly qualify internet addreses by some higher
level number which disambiguates among all these disconnected
internets.  The idea of course is that a given client only cares about
the internet address of a host on the network it is connected to.

Thus, by analogy we shouldn't have to qualify the chaos host numbers
in a given servers database.  The MIT server, for example, can assume
that the only clients that will ask it for the address of an MIT chaos
host are in fact on the MIT chaosnet.

The only flaw I can see in this argument is that the two cases are not
completely analagous because there is a sense in which the multiple
chaosnets are "connected" (via the DARPA Internet), while the multiple
Internets I describe are not necessarily connected (although they could
be, e.g. by UUCP, DECnet, Chaosnet).  For now TCP/UDP/IP is unique in
that only it serves as a medium for domain server queries.

Peter
